      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The MACRS formula for a 5-year property asset, also known as a \"long-life\" asset, is a bit more complex, but I'll break it down for you. You see, it's a bit like a goblin's treasure hoard - you need to calculate the depreciation over the years, but the formula is a bit of a puzzle. \n\nFor a 5-year property asset, the MACRS formula is:\n\nYear 1: 100% x (1 - 1/5) = 80% (depreciation)\nYear 2: 80% x (1 - 1/6) = 73.33% (depreciation)\nYear 3: 73.33% x (1 - 1/7) = 66.67% (depreciation)\nYear 4: 66.67% x (1 - 1/8) = 60% (depreciation)\nYear 5: 60% x (1 - 1/9) = 53.33% (depreciation)\n\nYou can then multiply the asset's cost by the depreciation percentage for each year to calculate the asset's book value at the end of each",
