    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The percentages I provided earlier were a bit of a miscalculation on my part. You're right, it's easier to just refer to the standard IRS table values for 5-year MACRS.\n\nFor a 5-year property asset, the standard IRS table values are:\n\nYear 1: 100%\nYear 2: 32.5%\nYear 3: 19.6%\nYear 4: 10.8%\nYear 5: 5.76%\n\nNow, as for the actual formula for the declining balance method, it's quite simple:\n\nDepreciation = (Cost - Accumulated Depreciation) x Depreciation Rate\n\nThe Depreciation Rate is the same as the MACRS rate for the year. So, for a 5-year asset, the Depreciation Rate would be 32.5% in Year 1, 19.6% in Year 2, and so on.\n\nFor example, if the asset cost $100,000 and the MACRS rate for Year 1 is 32.5%, the depreciation for Year 1 would be:\n\n$100,000 x 32.5% = $32,500\n\nAccumulated Depreciation",
      "source": "target",
